---
import Base from '~/layouts/Base.astro';

const faqs = [
  {
    q: 'Why is the repo called aiconsole-core and the binary opskern-console and the product aiconsole?',
    a: `OpsKern is the company that operates aiconsole. "aiconsole" is the product name on this site. "aiconsole-core" is the open-source repository that ships the product. "opskern-console" is the CLI binary — historical naming from when the CLI predated the product split. An "aiconsole" symlink shim is on the backlog so the public command matches the product name; until then, both names point at the same binary.`,
  },
  {
    q: 'How is this different from a DLP or a proxy?',
    a: 'DLPs and proxies run after the request leaves the machine — they detect, then react. aiconsole intercepts the prompt at the OS level before the request is built, classifies it with a local ruleset, and either redacts, blocks, or allows. The send never happens until aiconsole decides.',
  },
  {
    q: 'Which LLMs does it work with?',
    a: 'Claude, GPT, Gemini, Ollama, Cursor, and Copilot on day one. The capture layer is vendor-neutral — any desktop or CLI client that talks HTTPS is reachable. If you use a less common client, ask.',
  },
  {
    q: 'Does anything leave my machine?',
    a: 'No. The classifier, policy rules, and hash-chained audit log are all local. aiconsole does not send telemetry. The only network call from this site is your waitlist email, which goes to Buttondown.',
  },
  {
    q: 'What license is it under?',
    a: 'The desktop edition is Apache 2.0. Team Server (post-beta) will be BSL 1.1 with a two-year relicense to Apache 2.0. Enterprise licensing is custom. Each pricing tier lists the license explicitly — no surprises.',
  },
  {
    q: 'When does the waitlist open?',
    a: 'The form is live but intentionally disabled while we finish Buttondown DMARC + Turnstile wiring. It flips on during Phase A.1 of our launch plan — typically within a week of DNS going live.',
  },
  {
    q: 'How does the audit trail work?',
    a: "Every decision — allow, redact, block — is written to a hash-chained log. Each entry references the previous entry's hash, so a tampered entry invalidates every entry after it. The log is exportable for compliance review.",
  },
  {
    q: 'Can I run it air-gapped?',
    a: 'Yes. The desktop edition has no external network requirement. Enterprise adds signed attestations and a deploy kit for air-gapped environments.',
  },
];
---

<Base
  title="FAQ — aiconsole"
  description="Common questions about aiconsole, answered."
  noindex={true}
>
  <main class="w-full px-6 md:px-12 lg:px-16 py-section">
    <article class="max-w-prose mx-auto space-y-8 text-ink">
      <header class="space-y-2">
        <p class="font-mono text-sm text-ink-muted tracking-wide">aiconsole · from OpsKern</p>
        <h1 class="font-display font-bold text-4xl tracking-tight">Frequently asked</h1>
      </header>

      <dl class="space-y-8">
        {
          faqs.map(({ q, a }) => (
            <div class="space-y-2">
              <dt class="font-display text-xl text-ink">{q}</dt>
              <dd class="text-ink-muted">{a}</dd>
            </div>
          ))
        }
      </dl>

      <p class="font-mono text-xs text-ink-subtle tracking-wide pt-6">
        <a href="/" class="hover:text-accent">← aiconsole home</a>
      </p>
    </article>
  </main>
</Base>
